TRIP COMMENTS: This checklist is a combination of 11 point counts along the southernmost extension of the Coorong. They were distributed along the sw shore opposite Salt Creek. This was a deliberate census of the shorebirds using the area as part of studies conducted by Dr. David Paton.  Similar counts were also run elsewhere along the lagoon length. This is the portion of which I took part. Time of day is approximate. cool morning gave way to 20 C by end of census; strong 30 knot SSE wind kept shorebirds tight along the sw shore in the lee of the wind. Virtually no movement among flocks allowing for accurate counts.

TRIP COMMENTS: 0/10ths cloud. 24 deg C.  A day of walking through sand-dunes, low heath, mallee and white sand beaches searching for Rock Parrots.--A very satisfying day out.

In the area between Mclaughlin's Inlet and Mann's Beach by boat at half to low tide there were -- near McLaughlin's entrance, 60+ Fairy Terns, many sitting on eggs, 3 adult Hooded Plovers with two chicks, 1000s Red-necked Stints, 50+ Eastern Curlew, 6 Sooty Oystercatchers near Manns Beach, 75 Bar-tailed Godwit, 50+ Whimbrel, 100 Curlew Sandpiper. Offshore 1000+ unidentified Shearwaters. Reported by Duncan Fraser. Sighting 1122, .
There were 4 Hooded Plover at Point Roadknight back beach. Reported by Tony Trood. Sighting 1152, .

A walk along the ocean beach from French's Narrows to the mouth of the Snowy River was highlighted by a pair of Striated Fieldwrens calling in coastal dune scrub and a non breeding adult Ruddy Turnstone feeding along the tide line and 80+ Little Terns occupy the sand spit immediately to the east of the Snowy River mouth. Numerous nest scrapes and some eggs have already appeared. 7 Hooded Plovers were also counted. Reported by Len Axen. Sighting 740, .

TRIP COMMENTS: These observations were recorded by Dr. Ronald J. Ryel (1955-2015). Ron was the son of a wildlife biologist, and was birding by ear and sight from the age of six. He was an experienced and well-respected birder, serving many years on the Utah Bird Records Committee and having found seven new state records, for example. The data here were entered from Ron’s field notes by Andrew Durso. While we have every reason to expect that the written notes are accurate, we have attempted to enter all relevant available information here and will be unlikely to be able to provide additional details.

TRIP COMMENTS: There are currently several thousand waders feeding at Lake Victoria. Amongst them are several hundred Double-banded Plover and a dozen Banded Stilt. Among the many Curlew Sandpiper there are quite a few that are now in full red breeding plumage. It seemed unusual to see several Hooded Plover feeding amongst the migratory waders.  Reported by Rod Corinaldi and Tim Dolby. Sighting 1228, Lake Victoria, Point Lonsdale.

For the first time in six years or so of very frequent observations of birds on/around Lake Victoria I did not see a single red-necked stint today or for that matter any other migratory wader. There were plenty of red-capped plovers, 5 hooded plovers, a single Caspian tern and many chestnut teal and swans. This saline lake is now at the lowest level that I have seen in six years. Reported by Rod Corinaldi. Sighting 2488, Lake Victoria, Point Lonsdale.

TRIP COMMENTS: At the wetland at the top of Burrill Lake,looking from Cupitts Winery grounds at the end of Wilfords Lane, entered from the Slaughterhouse Rd at Ulladulla and not from Milton. There was app 40/50 Sharp-tailed Sandpipers, 30 Black-Winged Stilts, 2 Marsh Sandpipers and single Greenshank, Black-fronted Dotterel and Red-Kneed Dotterel being seen also. Oddly enough all the ducks have disappeared, whether this was because of the bushfires at the other end of the lake I don't know. Hooded Plovers are regulars on the Racecourse Beach (north end) at Ulladulla also. As the Winery grounds are private, permission should be asked at the premises before veiwing. A bit of a walk but worth it. Reported by Bob Rusk. Sighting 10241, Wilford Lane Wetlands at Cupitts Winery.

TRIP COMMENTS: Seven Hoodies with three D-Banded Plovers & 4 Redcaps were seen this morning on the beach. They had been regularly seen feeding on the rock shelved Nth end section of the beach until this week of heavy seas chased them off.   30+ Royal Spoonbills were spotted resting on the calm waters of Burrill lake making the count difficult owing to the reflections. Reported by Bob Rusk. Sighting 13571, Racecourse Beach. Sth. Ulladulla.

River entrance closed at present, Hooded Plover feeding along river edge where it meets sand berm. Plovers nest here, according to Moyne Shire Environment Officer. Brush Bronzewing flushed from Leucopogon / Acacia longifolia soph habitat on trail beside the river from the Yambuk slide carpark. This site was completely destroyed by floods in the 1940s where the river took the shortest route to the sea and removed a whole dune system. Since then coastal processes have rebuilt the dunes and they have naturally revegetated. Reported by Lisette Mill. Sighting 13595, Yambuk Coastal Reserve.

Hooded Plovers seen on S side of Point Roadknight over the weekend. Unfortunately I can't say much for the Anglesea locals' attitude to protecting these birds. With clear signage on the beach of no dogs, no less than 3 off-lead dogs on the N side of the point (right to the end) on Friday night (in 1 hour). Furthermore, on Sunday morning found multiple sets of dog tracks on the S side - where the Hoodies are currently breeding. From the looks of the tracks, the dogs were offlead and chasing something from the rocks down to the shore. Somehow the Hoodies were still there but sure left a bitter taste in the mouth to see such blatant disregard for bird conservation. What a shame. Reported by Jackson Airey. Sighting 15042, Point Roadknight, Anglesea.

TRIP COMMENTS: On Sunday afternoon with an incoming tide, 2 adult Hooded Plovers were seen feeding in the intertidal zone, in company with 3 Double-banded Plover and 5 Red-capped Plover.  After a period of feeding, the Hooded Plover and Double-banded Plovers all took up positions close to small clumps of seaweed.  2 Pied Oystercatcher and 1 Sooty Oystercater were on nearby exposed rocks.  The various plovers were not perturbed by the presence of a nearby lone beach fisherman (who was having a successful afternoon).   A short visit to Lake Tabourie the following morning netted 11 Red-capped Plover (in 3 groups) but no Hooded Plovers could be found. Reported by Jenny Madeline & Allan Ible. Sighting 13609, Cudmirrah Beach, Sussex Inlet.
SPECIES COMMENTS: adult

TRIP COMMENTS: A possible Arctic Tern in breeding plumage were seen during the course of regular shorebird surveys of the Noosa estuary on Tuesday, June 15. Also juvenile Hooded Plover. The plover was seen in several places in the smallish estuary on Tuesday and Wednesday. It moved around with the tide changes. There is a free public telescope mounted at the end carpark at Noosa Woods, which is accessed through Hastings Street. (See Bob Inglis photographs in further information).  Reported by Per Jill Dening. Sighting 13812, Noosa.

TRIP COMMENTS: Was amazed to see 6 Hooded Plovers at Lake Tabourie today, after dipping at almost every beach between there and Mallacoota, Vic. Of interest, 2 of the six were immatures, and both were the offspring of one of the pairs of adults (when a Sea Eagle flew over, they flushed, one pair of adults going one way, the other four, 2 adults, 2 immatures, another way). Also on the beach, 5 Double-banded Plovers, 4 Red-capped Plovers, 1 Red-necked Stint (must be overwintering as no sign of breeding plumage), as well as many Crested Terns, and Silver Gulls. A couple of Caspian Terns and Gannets seen. Worst thing was seeing dogs off leash, running about, and chasing the gulls. Reported by Ashwin Rudder. Sighting 13169, Lake Tabourie, south of Ulladulla.

TRIP COMMENTS: There appears to have been few follow-up visits to Clonmel Island since the initial reports in June so we decided to go and have a look. On a very nice winter's day, birds present were Australian Pied Oystercatcher (20), Sooty Oystercatcher (50), Grey Plover (10), Red-capped Plover (50), Double-banded Plover (200), Greater Sand Plover (10), Hooded Plover (2), Bar-tailed Godwit (1-2,000), Eastern Curlew (50), Ruddy Turnstone (1), Red Knot (200), Sanderling (100), Red-necked Stint (200), Curlew Sandpiper (5), Little Tern (7), Crested Tern (20), Pacific Gull (50) and Silver Gull (50) along with assorted gannets, pelicans, cormorants, herons, raptors, bronzewings and passerines. But, Semipalmated Plover (0), unfortunately. Reported by Chris Lester with Paul Dodd, Ruth Woodrow and Rosemary Lester. Sighting 14196, Clonmel Island, Corner Inlet.

(Note to moderators: This is a bit late as I've been away but may be of interest for your records) On a morning visit to Lake Conjola and nearby beach (the lake closed at present) sightings included a Hooded Plover with one immature, a Sanderling, a Red-necked Stint in breeding plumage, many Red-capped Plover and 8 Pied Oystercatchers. TRIP COMMENTS: Hooded Plover, Eastern Reef Egret. Also saw approx. 40 Bar-tailed Godwits on a distant sand bar inside the inlet, 30 to 40 Red-capped Plovers and about 20 Red-necked Stints. Dogs running loose on the beach are an issue here. Site:Bastion Point, Mallacoota. Observer:Andrew McCutcheon

TRIP COMMENTS: A nesting pair of Hooded Plover, scurrying across the sand, dodging the surfers and a group of beach cricketers. Met Stephen Johnson (volunteer Ranger), who had set up a protective barrier and wooden tent shelters for the birds eggs. (Thank you good Sir !!) There are currently a few nesting pairs along this strip of coast between Cape Paterson and Inverloch. Gary Lyon, (footy show commentator), was sitting on the sand behind me with his family, and so I asked him if he knew what this little Sea bird was? He replied  ' A Hooded Plover ' !!!  Some other birds observed in this area included a pair of Peregrine Falcon, Nankeen Kestrel, Roufous Whistler and an Eastern Yellow Robin. Reported by Con Baltas. Sighting 15963, East of Cape Paterson (off the Cape Paterson - Inverloch rd) small sheltered bay.
SPECIES COMMENTS: nesting pair

Hooded Plover. Six Hoodies seen within a 300 m stretch of beach and rock at Ulladulla on Sunday. An adult pair were seen at the southern end of Rennies Beach (near the roped off breeding area), and then a bit further south on the rock platform between Rennies and Racecourse Beaches were a family of 4, including two juveniles. (I went back to  make sure it wasn't the same two 'Rennies' adults but they were still there). It's great to think that perhaps they have successfully bred in the area, and justification to all the people roping off the breeding areas and putting up the signage. On Rennies Beach there were also a pair of Pied Oystercatchers, one of which had a metal band above the left knee and a yellow flag above the right with either 30 or 3D marked on it. Site:Ulladulla. Observer:Mark Ley

Waders & Albatrosses. Because of the strong winds and heavy seas, waders and birds of all sorts were sheltering in the estuary including 8 Hooded,19 Double Banded and 25 Red Cap Plovers along with 5 Bar-tailed Godwits,20 Masked Lapwings ,6 Caspian and 30 Crested Terns . This was all on a rapidly disappearing sand spit at the entry . Off shore was as busy with over 50 Albatrosses, both Black Browed and Shy types, Brown Skuas,Gannets and Shearwaters travelling at near sound barrier speeds Site:Burrill Lake Estuary. TRIP COMMENTS: Observations throughout the day.

Little Tern, Wedge-tailed Eagle, Banded Lapwing, Beautiful Firetail. Trip from 14 - 24 Jan, 73 species. Little Tern on the beaches at Cameron Inlet and Patriarch Inlet (with chick). At West End (Leeka), a Wedge-tailed Eagle adult perched and being circled by a Swamp Harrier which looked tiny by comparison. A juvenile Wedgie at Cameron Inlet was mobbed by a pair of Brown Falcons, one of which struck it in the back. Four Furneaux Islands endemic sub-species (Superb Fairy-wren, Tasmanian Scrubwren, New Holland Honeyeater & Black Currawong) are easily seen. Two adult & 2 young Banded Lapwings at a dam on an arid farm near Ranga. Family of Beautiful Firetails coming to drink at Pats River. Short-tailed Shearwater rookery at Port Davies is not to be missed, first birds nearby at 9.00pm, 70% landed by 9.45pm. Drive home very slowly due to Wallabies, Pademelons and Wombats. Migratory waders seen were Bar-tailed Godwit (North East River), Red-necked Stint (Patriarch Inlet & The Bluff), Ruddy Turnstone (Patriarch Inlet) and Common Greenshank (Lady Barron). White-bellied Sea-Eagles, Caspian Terns, Hooded & Red-capped Plovers on the beaches. Black-faced Cormorants on the rocks. Cape Barren Geese in the paddocks and Wild Turkeys, Common Pheasants & Indian Peafowl on the roadsides. Site:Flinders Island. Observer:Richard Case

Squally with very heavy rain showers. The tide rising and the river entrance and associated sandbanks being inundated by the strong surf. Spectacular to watch. This was our third visit here this week looking for Hooded Plovers which we and others have seen here in the past.

TRIP COMMENTS: I contemplated alternative hobbies as I stepped from the 23*C caravan in to 5*C reality, and crunched 100 metres through the frosty icy grass to access the estuary & beach. But these thoughts disappeared as I broke through the scrub and witnessed the dense morning mist brilliantly lit by the gold of the rising sun, and some 20 metres away the little Hooded Plover plying its trade along the estuary sands. As the Chestnut Teal swam by trying to tempt me in to the water, and the Yellow-tailed Blacks wailed & cooeed above me, I knew this is why I go birding.

Partnered with KE at the time.--VL – banded in February 2015 as a juvenile by Grainne Maguire, at Guvvos at Anglesea. It is a male and is almost 2.5 years old.--EH -  male banded by Grainne Maguire  as a chick pre-fledging at Pt Roadknight in Nov 2011 (making it 6.5 years old). It has set up as a breeder on the Bellarine with PC and they breed at 40W on Thirteenth Beach, near the site this sighting.

TRIP COMMENTS: Richard Weatherly
SPECIES COMMENTS: There were four juveniles and six flagged birds.  Orange flags were HH, EH, AY, and PC;  white flags were UU and AD. Following details, with thanks, to Grainne Maguire at BirdLife Australia: HH Orange is from Apollo Bay Barham River, banded as an adult in Dec 2012 – this is a really awesome sighting as we’ve never picked this bird up over on the Bellarine!--AD White was banded as a fledgling from Gunnamatta in March 2017! It’s lovely knowing this bird is doing well!--The below are locals and commonly use Blue Rocks:--EH Orange was a fledgling from Pt Roadknight tip in Sept 2011, it resides at 40-42W (just adjacent to Blue Rocks) --PC Orange was banded as a subadult (floater) in Aug 2010 at 13th beach 36W, it is female and partnered with AY – they reside at Bancoora 44W East. --AY Orange was banded as an adult at 40W in March 2011.--UU White was banded as an adult, it is a breeding adult from Ocean Grove and was rescued this year after it had an entanglement with hair around its foot.

This might well be one of the single best days in Orielton history! Everything one could hope for was there; perfect overcast lighting for dramatic photos, a cool that was bracing but not unpleasant, the beautiful blond rabbits of Golf Course Point... and even my first ever sighting of a Lizard for Orielton, a beautiful and very obliging Eastern Three-Lined Skink on one of the little logs by the Skylarks paddock! The only major detractor was the sheer skittishness of the Waders, of which so many kinds of so many individuals were present that the mind boggles! I had to go out past the Gull Colony, back to the Golf Course, back past the Gull Colony, and even wade, as the Waders all were, to escape the incredibly irritating attentions of the furious Kelp Gulls!! Oh, the Waders... Golden Plovers, Stints, Sharpies, Godwits... even Curlews at last returned to us, and the beautiful Pec!!! But the highlight? The astonishing highlight? Not only was it a first for me at Orielton, and one of the most appealing of all Waders, but it was the available records indicate that this gem was a FIRST EVER IN THE HISTORY OF ORIELTON!!!
SPECIES COMMENTS: This was absolutely the last thing I expected to find on my expedition out past the Gull Colony! I was photographing a fine flock of Red Caps, all of which were scurrying and halting in the nervous manner of their kind, when I suddenly noticed a different, larger bird pottering around behind them, slow yet never stopping, picking daintily at the mud! So big and pale was it that I knew something bizarre was afoot, even with only the first second of my view... and then I saw that head, that pitch black head, and the eye ring shockingly red! It was, in the usual manner of its kind, perfectly contented with being cautiously approached, albeit while seeming deeply confused and disorientated... as well it might! I don't mind saying I actually cursed out loud, such was my shock; after all, not only was this the first Hoodie I've ever seen at Orielton, a real favourite bird at my favourite site, and a Hoodie as far from its usual habitat as one can really hope to see, but according to the available records this bird was THE FIRST EVER HOODED PLOVER IN ORIELTON HISTORY!! And what a first!!

TRIP COMMENTS: There were intermittent showers during the day so the time (4 hours) covered two trips out, one in the morning and one in the afternoon.

TRIP COMMENTS: A really nice afternoon's exploration of the mudflats! I was really quite surprised to see the sheer diversity of waders, which was frankly worthy of Orielton Lagoon! The Stints and Double Banded Plovers were especially unworried by my examination of their little flock... that said, the reported relocated Orielton favourite, the Hudsonian Godwit, was absolutely not present, at least not while we were there.
SPECIES COMMENTS: A quite astonishing sight! No less than nine Hooded Plovers which, at first, were in a very close knit flock! Eventually, it became clear there were two different families involved, each with three juveniles and each cautiously happy to let me get some nice shots. It was very heartening to see such a successful breeding season, as I do love a nice Hoodie!

To say that today was far and away the best birding stroll I've ever had in Stanley would be quite simply the grossest understatement imaginable!! I decided to take in as many places as I could, and so I made my way right along the beach, back again, up the Nut, and then around a revelatory little track that ambles over the grassy lawns and knolls around the Nuts base; the numbers of truly fascinating birds on that little stretch of track was simply astonishing!! The highlight was fairly obviously the three different species of astounding Raptors, all of them putting on a fantastic show... but the birds in general were the highlight today!!
SPECIES COMMENTS: These three little nubbins of white stood out even from miles away, and their quietly industrious scurryings left me in no doubt as to what they were... and I was right! The fact they all posed together for their portrait, even feeding around each other's feet, made for some lovely photos and memories!

It is no exaggeration, and even less of a lie, to say that today was the most fun I have ever had birding in Tasmania!! The sun was bright as bright can be, the sand gleaming white, and the birds EVERYWHERE!! From the mind boggling Waders swarming the flats of the river just behind the dunes to the Little Terns constantly flying overhead, it was one of those days that I wished, in the moment of watching a Knot feeding, would never end. That’s not to say it wasn’t without its frustrations or perils; the first five hours turned up not so much as a breath of the Terek, while the tide coming in cut me off entirely from the way back to the car!! I struggled through up to my waist, thinking through my rising terror that this wasn’t so bad at all... and then, cruelly close to the beach, the water rose up to my neck!!! Being constantly pushed downriver, my feet sometimes flailing in nothing but water! Rattled and exhausted, I eventually flounder ashore in one piece and all was well!! However, I knew the loss of the Terek would haunt me if I didn't act while I was there... hence, we drove around to the other side of the river after settling our exhausted nerves, and that’s when the fun really started... as a passing note, there was also a very big, very dead Eagle Ray on the beach; an impressive sight indeed!
SPECIES COMMENTS: This little nesting pair in the sparkling white shell grit was a perfect little surprise!! I do love their quiet, plump contentment!

This was a bit of an impromptu trip but a very fun one indeed; Marion Bay never fails to deliver some gorgeous views, a remarkable treasury of shells and many good birds too!! The non bird highlight was probably the incredible number of Spider Crabs washed up from the sea; I've never seen any of these, dead or alive, in the wild before... and these were no small creatures; most had carapaces the width of my hand!!
SPECIES COMMENTS: It took us until we were well on our way back to the car to finally bag the Hoodeds... and it was so very worth the wait!! Be they in perfect silhouette with glowing outlines or scurrying at the waters edge, the warmth of the light really bringing out the best of them, the Hoodeds were as delightful as always, and watching them was a very blissful five or so minutes!!
